Ok, fair enough, I'll explain PoW immutability in an article. Explaining it over twitter is hard.
That energy creates a lower bound on the computational difficulty of re-calculating the chain. That is a security guarantee
Let's ignore terms. Do you get the idea that cumulative PoW is cumulative energy spend which must be re-spent to re-write chain?
Perhaps I know a few things about the correct use of security related terms. Tamper-proof is different from tamper-evident.
Immutability is the inability to change the past, not the inability to change it _without being noticed_. That's auditability
Different use case, both useful. Only one is actually immutable in a practical sense though
Come get your free tutorials on how Proof-of-Work works. Seven years in, still most don't understand it. I've ran 5 sessions today...
Valid proof-of-work is required to change the past and that requires more than mining consensus, it requires energy.
Incorrect. Hashing creates tamper-evident security. PoW creates tamper-proof immutability, it requires energy to change the past
